{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,240p' codex/prompts/04_report.md && printf '\\\\n--- outline ---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,240p' templates/report_outline.md\"","aggregated_output":"Read `AGENTS.md`, the hackathon submission guide, and fake-report walkthrough. Build a 4–8 page empirical report from real run IDs only. Never copy synthetic numbers. Include controls, chain diagnostics, uncertainty sources, runtime/cost, limitations, and reproducibility. Use cautious claim language. Verify every table cell against machine-readable real result files.\n\n--- outline ---\n# When Does a Model Learn Portuguese?\n\n**Status:** empirical / null / methodological — choose one. Do not reuse mock numbers.\n\n## Abstract\n\nQuestion, model/regime, controls, headline result with uncertainty, strongest limitation, safety relevance.\n\n## 1. Experimental design\n\nModel and training; data; controls; behavioral metrics; LLC protocol; checkpoint selection; preregistered criteria.\n\n## 2. Results\n\n### 2.1 Behavioral development\n\nTarget BPB, lexical metric, grammar margin, English retention.\n\n### 2.2 LLC and diagnostics\n\nRaw/normalized LLC, chain traces, running estimates, sensitivity.\n\n### 2.3 Controls and replication\n\nShuffled Portuguese, matched English, second seed.\n\n### 2.4 Optional intervention\n\nOnly when complete.\n\n## 3. Interpretation and limitations\n\nAssociation versus causality; transient-checkpoint issue; sampler sensitivity; model/domain/tokenizer limits; implications for Portuguese adaptation.\n\n## Reproducibility\n\nCommit, data hashes, run IDs, commands, environment, checkpoint hashes.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
