ases with held-out lexical combinations. Include nonce or templated cases if possible to reduce memorization.\n./docs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:116:Use a predeclared word-completion or translation-choice probe with held-out contexts. Report accuracy and continuous log-probability margins. Avoid evaluating on the exact training sentences.\n./docs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:120:Evaluate the unchanged English validation set at every checkpoint. Report relative BPB change and absolute BPB.\n./docs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:141:## 8. Diagnostics required for every reportable LLC\n./docs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:162:- model comparison: BIC and cross-validated error;\n./docs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:165:A reportable joint candidate requires:\n./docs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:183:5. report both grammar and target validation loss.\n./docs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:193:- **Sampler invalid on transient checkpoints:** methodological result; pivot to a controlled micro-language or report limitations rather than fabricate geometry.\n./docs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:3:The public Apart event page asks for a PDF research report documenting approach, results, and implications. The event welcomes technical-safety work on Portuguese- and Spanish-language models. The mock report uses six pages, within the previously identified 4–8 page target from an official hub page.\n./docs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:30:- report PDF;\n./docs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:33:- all real figures and source CSVs;\n./docs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:39:## Reporting language\n./docs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:51:A scientifically useful null report can show that Portuguese behavior improved smoothly, that LLC was insensitive or sampler-dependent, and that transient checkpoints violated local-posterior assumptions. The report should then emphasize the methodological lesson and provide the diagnostic benchmark rather than framing the result as failure.\n./docs/06_GCP_SETUP_AND_COST_GUARDRAILS.md