It establishes whether there is a behavioral phenomenon worth explaining.\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:34:Figure 1c shows normalized LLC rising and then dropping near the grammar change. The table reports structured Portuguese, shuffled Portuguese, and matched English side by side. The most useful fabricated detail is that shuffled Portuguese reaches high lexical accuracy but near-chance grammar and no LLC changepoint. That weakens a vocabulary-only explanation.\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:36:The page also reports English forgetting. A credible adaptation report should not pretend Portuguese capability is free.\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:46:The fake report localizes a susceptibility increase to a final MLP and freezes that component before the transition. The freeze delays grammar more than a matched control freeze. This is moderately good causal evidence, but capacity reduction remains a confound.\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:67:| Synthetic artifact | Real source |\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:72:| `figure_1b_grammar_margin.png` | evaluation pipeline output |\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:73:| `figure_1c_llc_trajectory.png` | chain-level LLC aggregation |\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:74:| `figure_s1_sampler_diagnostic.png` | raw sampler loss traces |\n./docs/09_FAKE_REPORT_WALKTHROUGH.md:77:Never edit synthetic CSV values into real tables. Generate a parallel `results/report/` tree from empirical run IDs.\n./scripts/validate_handoff.py:14:    \"reference/mock_report/slt_portuguese_synthetic_mock_submission.pdf\",\n./scripts/validate_handoff.py:15:    \"reference/mock_report/generate_synthetic_results.py\",\n./scripts/validate_handoff.py:24:pdf = ROOT / \"reference/mock_report/slt_portuguese_synthetic_mock_submission.pdf\"\n./scripts/validate_handoff.py:29:print(\"Validation passed. Synthetic artifacts remain under reference/mock_report/.\")\n./docs/05_CODEX_GCP_OPERATIONS.md:30:- checkpoints, traces, 