"state/experiment_registry.csv\\\"]}results/_codex/planner-001/final_decision.json\\n{\\\"terminal_decision\\\":\\\"continue\\\",\\\"stage\\\":\\\"infrastructure_gate\\\",\\\"executor_prompt\\\":\\\"codex/prompts/00_infrastructure_gate.md\\\",\\\"task_instruction\\\":\\\"Rerun the CUDA/infrastructure gate after the operator-side driver repair, but first perform a quick non-mutating check of `nvidia-smi`, PyTorch CUDA visibility, GPU name, driver/runtime versions, and free VRAM. If CUDA is still unavailable or `nvidia-smi` cannot communicate with the driver, update `state/current_status.json`, `state/decision_log.md`, and `state/experiment_registry.csv` with a fresh blocked infrastructure diagnostic and stop without attempting pilot work. Success criterion: `nvidia-smi` works, PyTorch reports one CUDA device with expected L4-class VRAM and at least 25% headroom, and the complete TinyStories-3M train-save-reload-evaluate-sample loop is either passed or produces a concrete infrastructure-gate artifact under `results/00_infrastructure_gate/<run_id>/`.\\\",\\\"time_budget_hours\\\":0.5,\\\"expected_cost_usd\\\":0.1,\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"AGENTS.md and the executive plan require the infrastructure gate before any pilot or final spend. The live state is blocked on CUDA driver repair, but this new unattended tick has no prior executor result in the current run, so the only useful bounded action is to verify whether the operator-side repair has taken effect and proceed with the official infrastructure gate only if CUDA is now healthy. The time and cost are capped tightly so a still-broken driver only produces a reportable blocked diagnostic.\\\"}results/_codex/planner-002/final_decision.json\\n{\\\"terminal_decision\\\":\\\"continue\\\",\\\"stage\\\":\\\"diagnose_and_fix\\\",\\\"executor_prompt\\\":\\\"codex/prompts/diagnose_and_fix.md\\\",\\\"task_instruction\\\":\\\"Diagnose the infrastructure blocker without launching training: inspect the current phase report/state, exact worker shell Python environment, CUDA device nodes, NVIDIA kernel/user-space driver consistency, `nvidia-smi`, `scripts/check_environment.py`, and PyTorch CUDA visibility. If a non-destructive user-level repair is available, such as activating an existing intended venv/conda environment, apply it and rerun only the preflight checks. Do not provision, resize, reboot, stop, delete cloud resources, install system drivers, or run TinyStories/training/sampler jobs. Success criterion: either fresh passing preflight artifacts that justify retrying the infrastructure gate, or updated state/report artifacts identifying a precise unrecoverable operator-side blocker and the minimal operator action needed.\\\",\\\"time_budget_hours\\\":0.5,\\\"expected_cost_usd\\\":0,\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"AGENTS.md requires the infrastructure gate before pilot/final work, and the executive plan makes this the first decisive gate. The last executor decision was blocked, so the sequencing rules call for a diagnose-and-fix tick rather than retrying the same infrastructure gate unchanged. This bounded zero-cost action may recover an environment activation issue or sharpen the CUDA/device-node diagnosis while preserving the remaining 7.9 hours and staying within the hard budget.\\\"}results/_codex/planner-003/final_decision.json\\n{\\\"terminal_decision\\\":\\\"escalate\\\",\\\"stage\\\":\\\"diagnose_and_fix\\\",\\\"executor_prompt\\\":\\\"codex/prompts/diagnose_and_fix.md\\\",\\\"task_instruction\\\":\\\"Halt for operator-side CUDA driver repair before any further experiment work. Required recovery: stop/start or reboot the VM from the operator side, rerun the official Google GPU driver installer if needed, verify `nvidia-smi` succeeds and PyTorch sees the L4, then resume with the infrastructure gate only.\\\",\\\"time_budget_hours\\\":0,\\\"expected_cost_usd\\\":0,\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"The infrastructure gate is blocked by a deterministic worker-visible driver failure: CUDA-enabled PyTorch is installed, the L4 is visible on PCI, and NVIDIA kernel modules are loaded, but `nvidia-smi` cannot communicate with the driver and PyTorch sees zero CUDA devices. The worker cannot perform cloud lifecycle or driver repair actions under AGENTS.md, and retrying pilot/final/LLC work would violate the gate order. This is not a spend approval issue; it is an external operator repair requirement.\\\"}\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./results/_codex/exec-diagnose_and_fix-002/events.jsonl:96:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_49\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' scripts/check_environment.py && printf '\\\\\\\\n--- tests ---\\\\\\\\n' && sed -n '1,220p' tests/test_cuda_diagnostics.py\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"from __future__ import annotations\\n\\nimport argparse\\nimport importlib\\nimport json\\nimport platform\\nimport subprocess\\nimport sys\\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\\nfrom pathlib import Path\\n\\n\\ndef classify_cuda_status(report: dict[str, object]) -> dict[str, str]:\\n    nvidia_smi = str(report.get(\\\"nvidia_smi\\\", \\\"\\\"))\\n    packages = report.get(\\\"packages\\\")\\n    torch_cuda_version = report.get(\\\"torch_cuda_version\\\")\\n    cuda_available = report.get(\\\"torch_cuda_available\\\") is True\\n    cuda_device_count = int(report.get(\\\"cuda_device_count\\\") or 0)\\n\\n    if cuda_available and cuda_device_count > 0 and not nvidia_smi.startswith(\\\"ERROR:\\\"):\\n        return {\\n            \\\"status\\\": \\\"cuda_available\\\",\\n            \\\"root_cause_hypothesis\\\": \\\"CUDA is visible to both nvidia-smi and PyTorch.\\\",\\n            \\\"recommended_action\\\": \\\"Proceed with the infrastructure gate.\\\",\\n        }\\n\\n    if isinstance(packages, dict) and str(packages.get(\\\"torch\\\", \\\"\\\")).startswith(\\\"ERROR:\\\"):\\n        return {\\n            \\\"status\\\": \\\"python_environment_missing_torch\\\",\\n            \\\"root_cause_hypothesis\\\": \\\"The active Python environment does not have PyTorch installed.\\\",\\n            \\\"recommended_action\\\": (\\n                \\\"Activate the intended Python 3.11 experiment environment, or install the required \\\"\\n                \\\"Python stack there, before rerunning the infrastructure gate.\\\"\\n            ),\\n        }\\n\\n    if not torch_cuda_version:\\n        return {\\n            \\\"status\\\": \\\"cpu_only_pytorch_wheel\\\",\\n            \\\"root_cause_hypothesis\\\": \\\"PyTorch was installed without CUDA runtime support.\\\",\\n            \\\"recommended_action\\\": \\\"Install a CUDA-enabled PyTorch wheel before rerunning the infrastructure gate.\\\",\\n        }\\n\\n    if nvidia_smi.startswith(\\\"ERROR:\\\") or cuda_device_count == 0:\\n        return {\\n            \\\"status\\\": \\\"operator_driver_repair_required\\\",\\n            \\\"root_cause_hypothesis\\\": (\\n                \\\"PyTorch has CUDA runtime support, but the NVIDIA driver/device is not usable \\\"\\n                \\\"from this worker.\\\"\\n            ),\\n            \\\"recommended_action\\\": (\\n                \\\"Operator-side VM stop/start or reboot, then rerun the official Google GPU \\\"\\n                \\\"driver installer; verify nvidia-smi before reinstalling Python packages.\\\"\\n            ),\\n        }\\n\\n    return {\\n        \\\"status\\\": \\\"unknown_cuda_failure\\\",\\n        \\\"root_cause_hypothesis\\\": \\\"CUDA is not available, but the driver and PyTorch probes disagree.\\\",\\n        \\\"recommended_action\\\": \\\"Preserve diagnostics and inspect driver/PyTorch compatibility before rerun.\\\",\\n    }\\n\\n\\ndef version(name: str) -> str | None:\\n    try:\\n        mod = importlib.import_module(name)\\n        return getattr(mod, \\\"__version__\\\", \\\"installed\\\")\\n    except Exception as exc:\\n        return f\\\"ERROR: {exc}\\\"\\n\\n\\ndef main() -> int:\\n    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--model\\\", default=None)\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--output\\\", type=Path, default=None)\\n    args = parser.parse_args()\\n\\n    report: dict[str, object] = {\\n        \\\"timestamp_utc\\\": datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(),\\n        \\\"python\\\": sys.version,\\n        \\\"platform\\\": platform.platform(),\\n        \\\"packages\\\": {k: version(k) for k in [\\\"torch\\\", \\\"transformers\\\", \\\"datasets\\\", \\\"devinterp\\\", \\\"numpy\\\", \\\"pandas\\\"]},\\n    }\\n    try:\\n        report[\\\"nvidia_smi\\\"] = subprocess.run(\\n            [\\\"nvidia-smi\\\"], check=True, text=True, capture_output=True, timeout=30\\n        ).stdout\\n    except Exception as exc:\\n        report[\\\"nvidia_smi\\\"] = f\\\"ERROR: {exc}\\\"\\n\\n    report[\\\"nvidia_device_nodes\\\"] = sorted(str(path) for path in Path(\\\"/dev\\\").glob(\\\"nvidia*\\\"))\\n    try:\\n        report[\\\"nvidia_driver_proc_version\\\"] = Path(\\\"/proc/driver/nvidia/version\\\").read_text(encoding=\\\"utf-8\\\")\\n    except Exception as exc:\\n        report[\\\"nvidia_driver_proc_version\\\"] = f\\\"ERROR: {exc}\\\"\\n\\n    try:\\n        import torch\\n        report[\\\"torch_cuda_available\\\"] = torch.cuda.is_available()\\n        report[\\\"torch_cuda_version\\\"] = torch.version.cuda\\n        report[\\\"cuda_device_count\\\"] = torch.cuda.device_count()\\n        if torch.cuda.is_available():\\n            report[\\\"cuda_device_name\\\"] = torch.cuda.get_device_name(0)\\n            report[\\\"cuda_total_memory_bytes\\\"] = torch.cuda.get_device_properties(0).total_memory\\n    except Exception as exc:\\n        report[\\\"torch_probe_error\\\"] = repr(exc)\\n\\n    if args.model:\\n        try:\\n            import torch\\n            from transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM, AutoTokenizer\\n            model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(args.model)\\n            tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from