: 1\\nconfigs/sampler_sweep.example.yaml:18:  num_chains: 2\\nconfigs/sampler_sweep.example.yaml:23:  num_chains: 3\\nconfigs/cost_model.example.json:3:  \\\"sampler_chain_steps\\\": 31700,\\nconfigs/final_tinystories8m_20260620.json:45:  \\\"llc_checkpoint_selection\\\": {\\nconfigs/final_tinystories8m_20260620.json:54:    \\\"freeze_note\\\": \\\"Use behavior outputs only. Do not inspect final LLC before this rule is written and the selected checkpoint file is frozen.\\\"\\ndocs/10_GO_NO_GO_CHECKLIST.md:10:- [ ] two sampler chains complete without NaNs/OOM.\\ndocs/10_GO_NO_GO_CHECKLIST.md:25:- [ ] one sampler configuration works at early/middle/late checkpoints.\\ndocs/10_GO_NO_GO_CHECKLIST.md:42:- [ ] chain-level diagnostics are included.\\nstate/current_status.json:3:  \\\"gate\\\": \\\"behavior_complete_llc_selection_frozen\\\",\\nstate/current_status.json:9:  \\\"structured_gate_decision\\\": \\\"proceed_to_llc\\\",\\nstate/current_status.json:31:  \\\"llc_checkpoint_selection\\\": {\\nstate/current_status.json:52:    \\\"no_final_llc_inspected\\\": true\\nstate/current_status.json:64:    \\\"llc_checkpoint_selection\\\": \\\"results/02_final_training/final_training_20260620T053855Z/llc_checkpoint_selection.json\\\",\\nstate/current_status.json:67:  \\\"next_action\\\": \\\"Run the LLC campaign using the frozen behavior outputs and selected checkpoint subset; do not retune per checkpoint.\\\"\\ndocs/11_FAILURE_MODES_AND_PIVOTS.md:17:Increase localization, test the predeclared `n_beta` alternatives, and inspect center loss. If no common configuration works across early/middle/late checkpoints, do not report comparable LLC. Pivot to:\\ndocs/11_FAILURE_MODES_AND_PIVOTS.md:49:Cut stretch experiments first. A coherent result with one main seed, controls, sampler diagnostics, and honest uncertainty is better than an unfinished intervention or multilingual comparison.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:9:A **geometric transition candidate** is a localized change in an SLT-derived estimate such as the Local Learning Coefficient (LLC), measured using a fixed localized posterior protocol and accompanied by acceptable chain diagnostics.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:39:| SGLD precision | FP32 |\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:47:Construct immutable train, validation, sampler-reference, and grammar-evaluation splits. The sampler-reference set must never overlap with training batches or the behavioral test set.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:80:The actual schedule may shift after the pilot, but it must be fixed before the final LLC inspection.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:84:LLC checkpoints:\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:87:- the two checkpoints bracketing the largest derivative in a behavioral metric selected without viewing LLC;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:122:## 7. LLC sampling protocol\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:124:At each selected checkpoint, define a localized posterior centered at checkpoint weights and use RMSProp-SGLD unless diagnostics justify another sampler.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:126:Use one fixed Portuguese sampler-reference set for all checkpoints of the structured Portuguese trajectory. Use the corresponding condition-specific reference set for each control. Keep fixed:\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:134:- sampler optimizer;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:139:Tune one global sampler configuration through a coarse-to-fine sweep described in `docs/02_SLT_BAYESIAN_COMPLICATIONS.md`. Never select a different “best” configuration for every checkpoint.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:141:## 8. Diagnostics required for every reportable LLC\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:144:- per-chain sampling-loss traces;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:145:- running LLC estimate per chain;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:146:- between-chain dispersion;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:148:- parameter displacement from the center checkpoint;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:150:- exact sampler settings;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:154:Reject or label exploratory any checkpoint whose chains keep moving downhill, fail to plateau, disagree substantially, or leave the intended local region.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:167:1. supported LLC slope/level change;\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:171:5. acceptable sampler diagnostics.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:190:- **Grammar transition without LLC change:** language learning occurred, but this LLC setup did not detect it.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:191:- **LLC change without behavioral change:** possible internal restructuring, incomplete probes, or sampler artifact.\\ndocs/01_RESEARCH_PROTOCOL.md:192:- **Smooth behavior and smooth LLC:** informative null result.\\ndocs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:10:| 2 | model, data, controls, hypotheses, metrics, sampler protocol |\\ndocs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:12:| 4 | LLC trajectory, controls, and final outcomes |\\ndocs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:22:- explicit evidence that sampler settings were not selected post hoc per checkpoint;\\ndocs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:34:- sampler traces;\\ndocs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:43:> We found an LLC changepoint in the same checkpoint interval as a rise in held-out Portuguese grammatical margin, with no corresponding joint pattern in shuffled-Portuguese or matched-English controls.\\ndocs/08_HACKATHON_SUBMISSION_GUIDE.md:51:A scientifically useful null report can show that Portuguese behavior improved smoothly, that LLC was insensitive or sampler-dependent, and that transient checkpoints violated local-posterior assumptions. The report should then emphasize the methodological lesson and provide the diagnostic benchmark rather than framing the result as failure.\\nstate/decision_log.md:9:Scientific scope: two structured Portuguese seeds, one shuffled Portuguese control, one matched English control; behavior at all checkpoints; reduced LLC replication; no Spanish or broad susceptibility scan until core result is complete.\\nstate/decision_log.md:23:Benchmark status: seq64 training, seq128 training, and the devinterp sampler smoke command were launched through `infra/remote/run_bounded_job.sh` and failed immediately because CUDA was unavailable. The full train-save-reload-evaluate-sample loop was not launched after the live GPU environment gate failed.\\nstate/decision_log.md:27:Failure mode and pivot: apply `docs/11_FAILURE_MODES_AND_PIVOTS.md` → GPU driver or PyTorch CUDA failure. Repair or restart the driver from the operator side, verify `nvidia-smi` and PyTorch CUDA before reinstalling packages, and rerun only the infrastructure gate. Do not proceed to pilot or final runs until the live loop, benchmarks, sampler smoke, and VRAM headroom pass.\\nstate/decision_log.md:49:planner escalated to a human: The infrastructure gate is blocked by a deterministic worker-visible driver failure: CUDA-enabled PyTorch is installed, the L4 is visible on PCI, and NVIDIA kernel modules are loaded, but `nvidia-smi` cannot communicate with the driver and PyTorch sees zero CUDA devices. The worker cannot perform cloud lifecycle or driver repair actions under AGENTS.md, and retrying pilot/final/LLC work would violate the gate order. This is not a spend approval issue; it is an external operator repair requirement.\\nstate/decision_log.md:68:driver. The TinyStories-3M model loop, sequence-length 64/128 training benchmarks, and devinterp sampler\\nstate/decision_log.md:126:TinyStories loop, training benchmark, sampler job, or long GPU job was launched.\\nstate/decision_log.md:148:sandbox saw only /dev/nvidia-caps and reported no CUDA. Operator authorized running the EXECUTOR with\\nstate/decision_log.md:159:planner escalated to a human: AGENTS.md forbids moving past infrastructure before CUDA, VRAM headroom, and the train-save-reload-evaluate-sample loop pass. The executive plan makes infrastructure the first decisive gate. The current state already contains repeated blocked infrastructure diagnostics and identifies an operator-side driver/device-node failure; the executor cannot repair VM lifecycle or driver state from the worker. Further pilot/final/LLC work would violate gate order, so a human/operator infrastructure action is required before useful bounded executor work can continue.\\nstate/decision_log.md:184:`train_seq64.json`, `train_seq128.json`, and `sampler_smoke.json` record completed benchmarks, and\\nstate/decision_log.md:185:`sampler_smoke.zarr/` preserves the raw devinterp smoke traces.\\nstate/decision_log.md:189:0.0744s with 55,082 tokens/s and 82.3% VRAM headroom. The sampler smoke ran 400 approximate chain steps\\nstate/decision_log.md:190:in 56.39s, estimated 0.1410s per chain step, wrote 9,547,222 bytes of trace output, and retained 85.6%\\nstate/decision_log.md:198:Uncertainty and failure modes: the sampler smoke uses random tokens and is explicitly not a scientifically\\nstate/decision_log.md:199:valid LLC estimate; it only validates the devinterp API/performance path and trace preservation. The\\nstate/decision_log.md:227:checkpoint trees with hashes under each condition, and early/middle/late sampler traces under\\nstate/decision_log.md:228:`llc_cross_check/*.zarr`.\\nstate/decision_log.md:234:sampler config produced finite early/middle/late LLC summaries and nonempty zarr traces.\\nstate/decision_log.md:243:the early/middle/late LLC traces are diagnostic rather than a formal SLT phase-transition claim. A\\nstate/decision_log.md:249:Decision: proceed to the LLC campaign with behavior outputs and checkpoint-selection rules frozen. No final LLC traces were inspected or optimized during final behavioral training.\\nstate/decision_log.md:251:Evidence: `results/02_final_training/final_training_20260620T053855Z/manifest.json`, `results/02_final_training/final_training_20260620T053855Z/data_splits/split_manifest.json`, condition summaries under `results/02_final_training/final_training_20260620T053855Z/conditions`, `results/02_final_training/final_trai